AWS EC2 + Docker Deployment — FULL MERGED
 GUIDE (Large Font + Bold Steps)
 Step 1 — Connect from Your Laptop (PowerShell)
 Use this command to connect to your EC2 Ubuntu instance.
 ssh -i "C:/Users/kaspa/.ssh/KASPA.pem" ubuntu@
 Replace with your instance's Public IPv4 address.
 Step 2 — Update Your EC2 Server
 Refresh the package index so the server installs software correctly.
 sudo apt update -y
 Step 3 — Install Docker + Essentials
 Install Docker, Git, and Nano editor on EC2.
 sudo apt install -y docker.io git nano
 sudo systemctl start docker
 sudo systemctl enable docker
 Enables Docker to start on system boot.
 Step 4 — Create Your Project Folder
 Make a directory to store your web files and enter it.
 mkdir aws-webapp && cd aws-webapp
 Step 5 — Create index.html
 Your website homepage. Shown when you open EC2-IP in browser.
 nano index.html
 (paste this text inside)
Hello from AWS
 Save: CTRL+O → Enter → CTRL+X
 Step 6 — Create the Dockerfile
 Defines how your Docker image will be built.
 nano Dockerfile
 (paste this)
 FROM nginx:alpine
 COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
 Nginx always looks inside /usr/share/nginx/html/ for index.html.
 Step 7 — Build the Docker Image
 Build your custom NGINX-based web image.
 sudo docker build -t mywebapp .
 Step 8 — Run the Web Container on Port 80
 Port 80 is the default web port for HTTP.
 sudo docker run -d -p 80:80 mywebapp
 Step 9 — Verify the Container Is Running
 Ensure your site container is active and port mapping is correct.
 sudo docker ps
 Should show → 0.0.0.0:80 -> 80/tcp
 Step 10 — View the Website in Your Browser
 Enter your EC2 Public IPv4 in browser:
 http://
Should display: Hello from AWS
 Optional — Stop or Remove Containers
 Useful for cleanup or re-deployment.
 sudo docker stop
 sudo docker rm
 Use docker ps to find the ID.
 Important Security Reminder
 Your EC2 security group MUST allow HTTP traffic.
 Allow inbound rule: HTTP (port 80) — Source: 0.0.0.0/0
 This makes your website accessible publicly.
